[4] Brazil (Ceara)
Date: 17 Feb 2007
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: O Povo [trans. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.opovo.com.br/opovo/fortaleza/671602.html>

In one week, the number of dengue cases increased 61 percent in Ceara
[State], according to a bulletin issued yesterday [18 Feb 2007] by
the state's Secretary of Health (SESA). There were 615 cases
confirmed in 37 municipalities. In the previous bulletin, 380 cases
were registered. The most critical situation is in Brejo Santo, in
the Cariri region, 508 km from the Capital, where there has been an
epidemic with 245 cases confirmed this year [2007], followed by
Reriutaba (82 [cases]), Forealeza (67 [cases], and Varjota (38 [cases]).
The number of DHF cases being investigated by SESA has also increased
from 4 to 10. One of the suspect cases [of DHF] was in Pacajus
(fatal), and the others were in Fortaleza (4 [cases]), Brejo Santo,
Quixelo, Maranguape, Sobral, and Santa Quiteria, with one case each.
According to the Coordinator of Public Policy of SESA, Manoel Dias de
Fonseca, this increase in disease [incidence] is due to the start of
the rainy season. This increase is worrisome, as we have dengue
[virus] types 1, 2, and 3, which [cause] an alert [situation] for DHF.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[2007, like 1998 and 2002, is shaping up to be another dengue year in
Brazil. _Aedes aegypti_ now is found in all units of the federation
and is expanding. Cases are occurring everywhere, but especially in
Mato Grosso do Sul state. - Mod.LJS]
[A map of Ceara state, Brazil, can be accessed at:
